rs to either</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> become a sponsored academy or </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">be dismissed and repla</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">ced by a DfE appointed Interim Executive Board</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> (IEB)</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">. </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> In December 2011 Downhills governors were given just a </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">few </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">weeks to make that decision.</span></li><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 32.11pt; padding-left:3.89pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">The school community was unconvinced by the government’s hyperbole about the success of academies in addressing t</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">he needs of disadvantaged children.</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> They were </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">concerned </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">by the lack of transparency in the</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> process</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> and by the Secretary of State’s zeal for only one unproven solution.</span></li><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 32.29pt; padding-left:3.71pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">The timing of the Downhills Ofsted was politically motivated.  Concerns have also been raised about the independence of Ofsted.  The impartiality of the DfE appointed IEB was </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">questioned: </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">two Harris Federation </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">senior </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">executives</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> (i.e. paid employees)</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">sat </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">on </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">the five person IEB.</span></li><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 32.29pt; padding-left:3.71pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Downhills parents were told by the DfE that academies did not fail</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> but we learned</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> that </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">the DfE could hand an academy </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">to another sponsor without any parent consultation. We knew that school improvement could be fragile and difficu</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">lt to </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">sustain, and we believed Downhills’ </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">best chance of security lay with</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">in</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> its local authority family of schools.</span></li><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 32.11pt; padding-left:3.89pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Downhills parents sa</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">w through the smoke and mirrors. </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> We knew that English schools </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">had been locally managed for decades and </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">were </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">already highly au</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">tonomous. </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> W</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">e knew that schools improved through focused leadership and good quality teaching</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">; t</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">here was no academy magic dust.  We </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">knew t</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">hat maintained schools in Haringey, in other parts of London and across the country were improving without handing ove</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">r </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">their </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">community assets to unelected, unaccountable chains.  We believed our children’s school had got caught up in the Secretary of State’s “Long March to reform our education system” (Daily Telegraph September 2010).   </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="2" type="A" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 32.93pt; padding-left:3.07pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Background</span></li></ol><ol start="6" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 32.66pt; padding-left:3.34pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">In October 2011 p</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">arents, governors </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">and staff learned</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12p