As well as an improving academic record, Downhills </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">had also been </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">good at the things that are harder to measure:</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> children’s</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> attitudes and</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> behaviour,</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> harmonious relati</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">onships, </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">excellent inclusive art and music provision.</span></li><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">The DfE</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> used </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">four pieces of evidence to justify its position</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> (see Annex 2)</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">.  All predate</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">d</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> the coalition academies and every one of these reports includes caveats about rolling out the programme.  Channel 4’s Fact Check advises “a dose of healthy scepticism appears to be needed whenever ministers seek to use statistics to prove the supposed sup</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">eriority of the academy model”.</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">  Meanwhile analysis</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> of the 2011</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">GCSE data by Henry Stewart of the </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Local Schools Network was showing </span><span 