at our Gypsy Roma </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">families would be turned away, that children w</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">ho had </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">SEN and</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> were</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> unlikely to reach a level 4 would no longer be encouraged to start at Downhills.</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">  Evidence provided to t</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">he Academies Commission</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">proved us right – segregation increases where schools are their own admission authorities. </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> </span></li><li style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; margin:5pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Race on the Agenda (</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">ROTA</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">)</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">'s 2013 survey of the 78 free schools (i.e. new academies) that opened in 2011 and 2012 found that the vast majority (87%) were not comply</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">ing with the statutory </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Public Sector Equalities Duties. </span></li></ol><ol start="4" type="A" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 33.77pt; padding-left:2.23pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">The process for approving, compelling and establishing academies and free schools, including working with sponsors</span></li></ol><ol start="14" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">The Secretary of State said </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">in 2010 </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">that his Department had identified 200 underperforming primary schools which would benefit from academisation</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">, but Downhills was nowhere near the bottom 200.  In fact there was no list and the DfE was intent on forcibly academising those school</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">s where it h</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">ad legal power to dismiss</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> the governing body and install an IEB i.e. schools in Special Measures.</span></li><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">In December 2011, t</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">he DFE </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">academy brokers</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> visited Downhills</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">.  </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">The </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">officials</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> threatened the governors </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">that, if they didn’t want things to be more turbulent for</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> the school should agree - by mid January - to become an academy.  I would have taken longer to get quotes to decorate my house than the governing body was being given to decide to give away our community school. And this decision was irreversible</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">.</span></li><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">We have</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> since learned that academy brokers are active around the country, charging the taxpayer telephone number fees.  Brokers ask governing bodies to imagine they are frogs in a pan of water with the heat being turned up; they advise them to </span><span style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">convert before bein</span><span style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">g forced to do so.  Democratically accountable local volunteers are being pressured to jump before they are boiled.</span></li><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">In September 2011 Ofsted HMI had reported that Downhills</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">was making satisfac</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">tory progress in addressing </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">issues for improvement and in raising the pupils’ achievement. </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Then </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">just 13 weeks later in January 2012, </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">the same HMI revisited the school</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> and found </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">insufficient progress.  </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">It is very difficult for parents and others to have confidence in </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Ofsted when HMI’</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">s </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">judgements are so variable in such a short period of time.    </span></li><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Without doubt, the timing of the January </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">2012 </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">inspection was politically motivated; the inspection was c</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">alled by the Secretary of State when h</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">e had no educational or safeguarding evidence </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">to </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">do so. </span></li><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">In mid February 2012, fearing a press leak after being contacted by a journalist from a national education newspaper, our Headteacher told parents about the Ofsted special measures judgement and stood down. We lost an honourable and experienced lea</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">der. The governing body wrote an open letter to Mr Gove asking to meet him or his officials.  Governors said that they would discuss all options for school improvement, including academy status.  That meeting was scheduled for 8 March.</span></li><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">It was becoming clea</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">r that Mr Gove wanted </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">the </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Harris Federation to sponsor the academy.  Founded by Conservative donor and former</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> party</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> treasurer, Lord Phil Harris, the Federation ran a chain of academies in South London, but at the time only one primar</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">y</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">, and </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">with no </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">links to Tottenham.  </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Our governors asked why Harris was best but received no answer.  They also asked to speak with other sponsors and for time for a full consultation. </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Parents</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> asked under the FOI for information </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">about sponsor se</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">lection but </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">the request was</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">refused</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> by the DfE</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">.</span></li><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Meanwhile go</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">vernors started a consultation and e</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">ven after the poor Ofsted report and the resignation of the Head, 147 parents voted against the school becoming an academy, 14 voted ‘yes’ and five ‘don’t know’. 91% of parents had voted </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">‘no academy’.</span></li><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">In March our governing body was dismissed and replaced by an interim executive board (IEB). The Secretary of State had signed an academy order naming H</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">arris as the sponsor.  To parents’ amazement</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">, he also named senior Harris executives as two</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> of the five IEB members. Mr Gove has asked the IEB to consult and to make a recommendation on whether the school should convert to an academy, and whether Harris should be the sponsor.  The Chair of the IEB assured </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">parents</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> t</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">hat the two Harris members woul</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">d </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">leave the room when that decision </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">was</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> made. </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">The IEB launched a massive consultation exerci</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">se costing in excess of £45,000.  </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">This time </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">94% o</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">f our community said no academy. </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">  </span></li><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">T</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">hree other Haringey primaries had been identified by the DfE</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> for forced co